from:"Some Skomer sounds", 2004, Rombout de Wijs. In 1982 and 1983 I was a research assistant on Skomer Island for counting, observing and ringing seabirds. In my spare time I made many pictures and also recoded sounds of several birds. The main purpose was to document the state of island life at that time, also enabling me to relive my stay (to some extent) in later years. Sound recordings were made with rather primitive means, two simple microphones mounted in the "focal point" of a plastic umbrella (used as a reflector), a Sony TCS-310 stereo cassette recorder and simple headphones. Only recently I decided to make them better available and therefore digitized them. From 3.5 hours of sounds I extracted this selection for audio cd.

Oystercatcher piping display.

Recorded with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 attached to the side of the hide. Edited below 2000 Hz to remove background traffic noise.

"Kleep" calls from Oystercatchers flying past followed by simultaneous piping displays from two rival birds in the second half. 

Recorded with an Olympus LS-12 and Sennheiser ME66 loosely fixed to a hide. Moderately edited below 2000 Hz to reduce road noise.

The track opens with a typical "kleep" calls followed by "pip" calls that develop into a full-blown piping display. The piping display uses disylabbic notes. 
There are "poot" calls from 1:20 which can be considered to be a continuation of the piping. At 2:09 there is an odd bubbling which I think is also an Oystercatcher call. 
There are also Oystercatcher pip calls from 2:13 which develop into a much shorter period of piping. The track finishes with more poot calls.
